sentences: Lea Luboshutz (February 22, 1885 – March 18, 1965) was a Russian violinist.
Lea came to the Moscow Conservatory at age 11, on an invitation by Vasily Safonov, and ended her studies there winning the gold medal in May 1903.
She quickly became well established in Moscow musical circles  and began to tour in Russia and eastern Europe.
During the summer of 1905, Lea went to Belgium for post-graduate studies with Eugène Ysaÿe.
During the summer of 1905, Lea went to Belgium for post-graduate studies with Eugène Ysaÿe.
Lea made her first trip to the United States in 1907 but her tour was cut short by pregnancy.

Following the Russian Revolution , Goldovsky and Luboshutz decided to emigrate and she departed, first going to Germany on a concert tour in 1921 with her 13-year-old son Boris serving as her accompanist, never to return.
